  "content": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "JavaScript Booleans"
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "The Boolean Data Type\nIn JavaScript, a Boolean is a primitive data type that can only have one of two values:\ntrue or false\nThe Boolean value of an expression is the basis for all JavaScript comparisons and \nconditions."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Key Boolean Characteristics"
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "true and false are boolean data types\ntrue and false are the only possible boolean values\ntrue and false must be written in lowercase\ntrue and false must be written without quotes"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Boolean Use Cases"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Very often, in programming, you will need a data type that can represent one \nof two values, like:"
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "yes or no\n  on or off\n  true or false"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Boolean values are fundamental for logical operations and control flow in JavaScript programming."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Comparisons"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "All JavaScript comparison operators (like ==, !=, <, >)\nreturn true or false from the comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Given that x = 5, the table below explains comparison:"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [],
        [
          "Description",
          "Example",
          "Returns"
        ],
        [
          "Not equal to",
          "(x == 8)",
          "false"
        ],
        [
          "Unequal to",
          "(x != 8)",
          "true"
        ],
        [
          "Greater than",
          "(x > 8)",
          "false"
        ],
        [
          "Less than",
          "(x < 8)",
          "true"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 5;\n\n(x == 8); // equals false\n(x != 8); // equals true"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "See Also:\nJavaScript Comparisons Tutorials"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Conditions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Booleans are extensively used in if statements to determine the code blocks to execute based on the logic."
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [],
        [
          "Example",
          "Result"
        ],
        [
          "if (day == \"Monday\")",
          "true or false"
        ],
        [
          "if (salary > 9000)",
          "true or false"
        ],
        [
          "if (age < 18)",
          "true or false"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "if (hour < 18) {\n  greeting = \"Good day\";\n} else {\n  greeting = \"Good evening\";\n}"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "See Also:\nJavaScript If Else Tutorial"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Loops"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Booleans are extensively used in loops to determine conditions for looping."
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "data": [
        [],
        [
          "Description",
          "Example"
        ],
        [
          "For loop",
          "for (i = 0; i < 5; i++)"
        ],
        [
          "While loop",
          "while (i < 10)"
        ],
        [
          "For in loop",
          "for (x in person)"
        ],
        [
          "For of loop",
          "for (x of cars)"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "while (i < 10) {\n  text += i;\n  i++;\n}"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "See Also:\nJavaScript Loop Tutorial"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "The Boolean() Function"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "You can use the Boolean() function to find out if an expression (or a variable) is \ntrue:"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "Boolean(10 > 9)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Or even easier:"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "(10 > 9)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Everything With a \"Value\" is True"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "100 is true\n3.14 is true\n-15 is true\n\"Hello\" is true\n\"false\" is true\n(7 + 1 + 3.14) is true"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Everything Without a \"Value\" is False"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 0;\nBoolean(x);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = -0;\nBoolean(x);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = \"\";\nBoolean(x);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x;\nBoolean(x);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = null;\nBoolean(x);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = false;\nBoolean(x);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = 10 / \"Hallo\";\nBoolean(x);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "JavaScript Booleans as Objects"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Normally JavaScript booleans are primitive values created from literals:"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = false;"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "But booleans can also be defined as objects with the keyword new:"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let y = new Boolean(false);"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = false;\nlet y = new Boolean(false);\n //\ntypeof x returns boolean\n //\ntypeof y returns object"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "Warning\nDo not create Boolean objects.\nThe new keyword complicates the code and slows down execution speed.\nBoolean objects can produce unexpected results:"
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "description": "",
      "codes": [
        {
          "language": "unknown",
          "code": "let x = Boolean(false);\nlet y = new Boolean(false);\n\n(x == Y) returns true\n(y === Y) returns false"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "Comparing two JavaScript objects always returns false."
    },
    {
      "type": "other",
      "text": "Complete Boolean Reference\nFor a complete reference, go to our Complete \nJavaScript Boolean Reference.\nThe reference contains descriptions and examples of all Boolean properties and methods."
    }
  ]
}